00:24:33,000 --> 00:24:36,000
And that prevailed until

265
00:24:36,000 --> 00:24:41,000
rather late in the history of the institution.

266
00:24:42,000 --> 00:24:45,000
What you see along on our own street now is a lot of places

267
00:24:45,000 --> 00:24:48,000
where you can get beer and other things in the students

268
00:24:48,000 --> 00:24:51,000
or clearly enjoying their Fridays like today

269
00:24:51,000 --> 00:24:55,000
at the Brew Station, for example.

270
00:24:55,000 --> 00:24:58,000
But on those days you couldn't get it.

271
00:24:58,000 --> 00:25:02,000
In fact, Oregon,

272
00:25:02,000 --> 00:25:07,000
I forgot in what the date of the overturning of prohibition was,

273
00:25:07,000 --> 00:25:10,000
but alcohol was slow to come to Oregon.

274
00:25:10,000 --> 00:25:16,000
In the sense that, first of all,

275
00:25:16,000 --> 00:25:18,000
you could only buy it in the green front.

276
00:25:18,000 --> 00:25:21,000
You couldn't buy it in a restaurant.

277
00:25:21,000 --> 00:25:25,000
But you could bring your bottle in a restaurant

278
00:25:25,000 --> 00:25:30,000
and they would charge you a corkage fee

279
00:25:30,000 --> 00:25:35,000
and serve you.

280
00:25:35,000 --> 00:25:39,000
But that's a long time for that to be overturned.

281
00:25:39,000 --> 00:25:46,000
So there's one incident that I can tell you about

282
00:25:46,000 --> 00:25:50,000
that I mentioned it before, but it was really quite remarkable.

283
00:25:50,000 --> 00:25:55,000
I think it was in the winter of 1941.

284
00:25:55,000 --> 00:25:59,000
I think it was before Pearl Harbor.

285
00:25:59,000 --> 00:26:03,000
When we had a tremendous ice storm,

286
00:26:03,000 --> 00:26:06,000
I don't know whether you heard about this ice storm,

287
00:26:06,000 --> 00:26:11,000
but what happened was we had a freezing rain.

288
00:26:11,000 --> 00:26:15,000
And this was on the night of one of the old school dances,

289
00:26:15,000 --> 00:26:18,000
which were held by the way in the Memorial Union Ballroom.

290
00:26:18,000 --> 00:26:22,000
The size of the institution when I first in the fall,

291
00:26:22,000 --> 00:26:27,000
maximum size was, I remember, 4,200 students.

292
00:26:27,000 --> 00:26:31,000
So the MU Ballroom could generally contain all the people

293
00:26:31,000 --> 00:26:35,000
that wanted to go to a formal dance.

294
00:26:36,000 --> 00:26:40,000
A lot of people couldn't afford going, so they didn't.

295
00:26:40,000 --> 00:26:43,000
Well anyway, in the MU on this particular occasion,

296
00:26:43,000 --> 00:26:47,000
there was an ice storm that began early in the evening

297
00:26:47,000 --> 00:26:50,000
and people began to show up.

298
00:26:50,000 --> 00:26:53,000
And as the evening drew on,

299
00:26:53,000 --> 00:26:58,000
the rain which had continued

300
00:26:58,000 --> 00:27:03,000
began to develop into a freezing rain.

301
00:27:03,000 --> 00:27:08,000
And the trees began to be branches began covered with ice.

302
00:27:08,000 --> 00:27:12,000
All the power lines were covered with ice.

303
00:27:12,000 --> 00:27:17,000
And as the dance went on, all of a sudden,

304
00:27:17,000 --> 00:27:24,000
the maybe 839 o'clock, the lights went out.

305
00:27:24,000 --> 00:27:27,000
And what had happened, of course,

306
00:27:27,000 --> 00:27:30,000
is that the power lines were down because of the weight of the ice

307
00:27:30,000 --> 00:27:32,000
and so on.

308
00:27:32,000 --> 00:27:35,000
Well, this is an all-school dance and it was dark.

309
00:27:35,000 --> 00:27:38,000
You see, no lights in the MU Ballroom.

310
00:27:38,000 --> 00:27:41,000
So somebody scrounced up the candles

311
00:27:41,000 --> 00:27:45,000
and put them around the edge or some other form of light.

312
00:27:45,000 --> 00:27:48,000
But the MU lounge, which is very much the same as it is now,

313
00:27:48,000 --> 00:27:51,000
is a place where, in these dances,

314
00:27:51,000 --> 00:27:55,000
couples would repair, to rest a while and sit,

315
00:27:55,000 --> 00:27:57,000
smooch with each other.

316
00:27:57,000 --> 00:27:59,000
And when the lights went out,

317
00:27:59,000 --> 00:28:03,000
she could imagine the glee that that was greeted with,

318
00:28:03,000 --> 00:28:06,000
well, then after a show,

319
00:28:06,000 --> 00:28:08,000
I happened to be up in the lounge at the time,

320
00:28:08,000 --> 00:28:11,000
with my girlfriend at the time.

321
00:28:11,000 --> 00:28:14,000
And the lights went out and,

322
00:28:14,000 --> 00:28:15,000
and, due course,

323
00:28:15,000 --> 00:28:18,000
there came one of the shopper-alls.

324
00:28:18,000 --> 00:28:20,000
Usually a wife of a faculty member,

325
00:28:20,000 --> 00:28:23,000
she came in with a large candle opera.

326
00:28:23,000 --> 00:28:25,000
With lighted candles,

327
00:28:25,000 --> 00:28:28,000
and she put it on a big table in the middle of the room.

328
00:28:28,000 --> 00:28:31,000
And then she turned around and she walked,

329
00:28:31,000 --> 00:28:34,000
and she walked back to the down the stairway down into the ballroom.

330
00:28:34,000 --> 00:28:37,000
She got to the head of the stairs and disappeared.

331
00:28:37,000 --> 00:28:40,000
One of the students there got up,

332
00:28:40,000 --> 00:28:42,000
walked over to the candle,

333
00:28:42,000 --> 00:28:45,000
and all the candles out to the great chairs.

334
00:28:45,000 --> 00:28:49,000
And a few minutes,

335
00:28:49,000 --> 00:28:52,000
the same woman came back,

336
00:28:52,000 --> 00:28:55,000
and she lit the candles again.

337
00:28:56,000 --> 00:28:58,000
And she turned around and walked away,

338
00:28:58,000 --> 00:29:02,000
but she didn't get to the head of the stairs this time before the student,

339
00:29:02,000 --> 00:29:05,000
maybe the same one went up and blew them out again.

340
00:29:05,000 --> 00:29:07,000
Again, to great chairs,

341
00:29:07,000 --> 00:29:10,000
this time she never returned.

342
00:29:10,000 --> 00:29:12,000
And turned out,

343
00:29:12,000 --> 00:29:16,000
the lights were out as a consequence of that storm

344
00:29:16,000 --> 00:29:19,000
for the best part of a week.

345
00:29:19,000 --> 00:29:21,000
And that was devastating,

346
00:29:21,000 --> 00:29:25,000
it was extremely hard for my mother,

347
00:29:25,000 --> 00:29:30,000
because we cooked on an electric stove.

348
00:29:30,000 --> 00:29:33,000
And we had all these students there,

349
00:29:33,000 --> 00:29:36,000
four of them plus my sister and myself.

350
00:29:36,000 --> 00:29:39,000
So she prepared the meals

351
00:29:39,000 --> 00:29:43,000
as best she could using pots and pans

352
00:29:43,000 --> 00:29:45,000
and so on in the fireplace.

353
00:29:45,000 --> 00:29:47,000
We had a fireplace fortunate,

354
00:29:47,000 --> 00:29:49,000
and she could build a fire and do that.

355
00:29:49,000 --> 00:29:52,000
So essentially we camp for a week,

356
00:29:52,000 --> 00:29:54,000
remarkable experience,

357
00:29:54,000 --> 00:29:55,000
well,

358
00:29:55,000 --> 00:29:57,000
as far as the campus was concerned,

359
00:29:57,000 --> 00:29:59,000
the consequences of that ice storm

360
00:29:59,000 --> 00:30:01,000
were devastating.

361
00:30:01,000 --> 00:30:04,000
The campus in front of the MU at the time

362
00:30:04,000 --> 00:30:07,000
was covered in large numbers

363
00:30:07,000 --> 00:30:10,000
of a large number of trees,

364
00:30:10,000 --> 00:30:12,000
beautiful trees.

365
00:30:12,000 --> 00:30:15,000
Perhaps many of them Elm trees,

366
00:30:15,000 --> 00:30:17,000
I don't know.

367
00:30:18,000 --> 00:30:21,000
The ice storm actually broke the branches

368
00:30:21,000 --> 00:30:23,000
off of these trees to the point

369
00:30:23,000 --> 00:30:25,000
where it looked like a tornado

370
00:30:25,000 --> 00:30:27,000
and hit that section of the campus.

371
00:30:27,000 --> 00:30:29,000
You could walk through it in the daytime

372
00:30:29,000 --> 00:30:31,000
and it was still freezing.

373
00:30:31,000 --> 00:30:33,000
You could still see the ice,

374
00:30:33,000 --> 00:30:35,000
branches lying everywhere on their trees

375
00:30:35,000 --> 00:30:37,000
effectively denuded

376
00:30:37,000 --> 00:30:39,000
of their branches.

377
00:30:39,000 --> 00:30:42,000
Well, I led to the removal of most of the trees

378
00:30:42,000 --> 00:30:44,000
in front of the Memorial Union.

379
00:30:44,000 --> 00:30:46,000
I suppose it was true

380
00:30:46,000 --> 00:30:48,000
that this is only campus also.

