754
00:54:47,000 --> 00:54:51,000
The war work was going on in the chemical industry.

755
00:54:51,000 --> 00:54:59,000
And in particular, there were people from Shell Development Company who came around,

756
00:54:59,000 --> 00:55:07,000
and they were looking for people who recommended by the faculty to do war work on some of their projects.

757
00:55:07,000 --> 00:55:13,000
The other opportunity, and I was interviewed by them and offered a job.

758
00:55:13,000 --> 00:55:21,000
The other opportunity was to go into the Air Force in a program that would have been,

759
00:55:21,000 --> 00:55:33,000
for me, and meteorology, or an armament, not in flying, because at the time, my visual acuity wasn't very good.

760
00:55:33,000 --> 00:55:40,000
And so I had been registered with a draft board, and I went to see Gilbert.

761
00:55:40,000 --> 00:55:47,000
And Gilbert, he was a nice guy, I liked him a lot.

762
00:55:47,000 --> 00:55:54,000
But he kind of grumbled, or, you know, he would talk in a little voice.

763
00:55:54,000 --> 00:55:58,000
He said, I think it's ridiculous for you to go into the Air Force.

764
00:55:58,000 --> 00:56:02,000
And not use your chemical training when you could do that.

765
00:56:02,000 --> 00:56:06,000
In war work, for they need skilled people.

766
00:56:06,000 --> 00:56:13,000
And so then I went down to my draft board, and I talked to the chairman of a draft board.

767
00:56:13,000 --> 00:56:18,000
And I think his name was Cindy McCollum, or something like that.

768
00:56:18,000 --> 00:56:21,000
I thought he was clearly a scot.

769
00:56:21,000 --> 00:56:24,000
And he ran a gas station down town.

770
00:56:24,000 --> 00:56:28,000
And I explained this situation to him.

771
00:56:28,000 --> 00:56:35,000
And you said, young man, you better go in the Air Force, or we're going to draft you.

772
00:56:35,000 --> 00:56:42,000
Well, this calls me to think a little bit about this.

773
00:56:42,000 --> 00:56:49,000
And at that point, I knew I wanted to go to graduate school, you see.

774
00:56:50,000 --> 00:56:55,000
To make a long story short, I finally decided that I would take the job at Shell Development Company,

775
00:56:55,000 --> 00:57:02,000
which was a professionally extraordinarily valuable experience.

776
00:57:02,000 --> 00:57:12,000
But in terms of emotional contentment, it certainly wasn't very relaxing.

777
00:57:13,000 --> 00:57:20,000
First of all, I spent most of the war on one A, which is the draft status eligible for a draft.

778
00:57:20,000 --> 00:57:27,000
And you never know whether you're going to be drafted.

779
00:57:27,000 --> 00:57:32,000
And well, I guess I shouldn't have said it that way.

780
00:57:32,000 --> 00:57:38,000
When you're in one A, you're eligible to be drafted, and will be drafted.

781
00:57:38,000 --> 00:57:45,000
So, I was always classified one A by the draft board.

782
00:57:45,000 --> 00:57:54,000
The company appealed to the appeal board at Oregon on grounds, and I was doing war work and supplied the paper.

783
00:57:54,000 --> 00:58:00,000
There are a vacation of this, and because of the secretive and important nature of this war work,

784
00:58:00,000 --> 00:58:06,000
I was always reclassified in different stages of to be.

785
00:58:06,000 --> 00:58:20,000
Now, this deferred status lasted for only six months, dated from the time that you were first classified one A.

786
00:58:20,000 --> 00:58:33,000
Well, it took about three months for this process to go on, and for you to be reclassified to be, but by that time you only had three months left.

787
00:58:34,000 --> 00:58:47,000
So, I spent literally half of the entire war years in one A while the process of keeping me deferred to do this war work went on.

788
00:58:47,000 --> 00:58:58,000
And it's more than just paperwork, because before you're classified one A, you get a notice on the draft board that says greetings.

789
00:58:58,000 --> 00:59:01,000
And then you have to appear for a physical.

790
00:59:01,000 --> 00:59:07,000
Well, they would tell you when you first of all, I had to appear at fifth and one rule for a physical.

791
00:59:07,000 --> 00:59:11,000
So, I can't do that. I mean, we're engaged in war work down here.

792
00:59:11,000 --> 00:59:17,000
We'll transfer your physical down there all this took time, you see.

793
00:59:17,000 --> 00:59:21,000
So, then I would take the physical, or I would go down.

794
00:59:21,000 --> 00:59:25,000
I'd be transported to San Francisco after the procedure.

795
00:59:25,000 --> 00:59:33,000
And there are a whole bunch of potential draftes were lined up, and we went through a physical, it took at least.

796
00:59:33,000 --> 00:59:37,000
Well, it took all morning, and the most of the afternoon.

797
00:59:37,000 --> 00:59:43,000
A which time?

798
00:59:43,000 --> 00:59:55,000
You either classified as physically capable or classified four F, which means incapable of military service.

799
00:59:55,000 --> 01:00:02,000
So, at the end of this, I was classified one A. My draft board was notified, and they told me I was one A.

800
01:00:02,000 --> 01:00:09,000
Then the company would get the papers, and they would appeal this, and we would go through the whole thing again.

801
01:00:09,000 --> 01:00:18,000
I did that about five times, I think, during the war.

802
01:00:18,000 --> 01:00:27,000
And on one occasion, just before the war was ending both in the Pacific, both in the European theatre,

803
01:00:27,000 --> 01:00:36,000
was in 1945, and I had an emergency appendectomy, and those days an emergency appendectomy was a big deal.

804
01:00:36,000 --> 01:00:44,000
I was in the hospital in Oakland for over a week, bedridden. They didn't allow you to get up or anything.

805
01:00:44,000 --> 01:00:48,000
I had a huge scar like this long there.

806
01:00:48,000 --> 01:00:52,000
So anyway, in the middle of all this, my notice to appear for a physical part.

807
01:00:52,000 --> 01:01:00,000
But I knew that if you had a recent serious operation, and that was serious in those days, you're automatically deferred for six months.

808
01:01:00,000 --> 01:01:06,000
So, I tried to tell them that I'd add a recent appendectomy, so take your physical.

809
01:01:06,000 --> 01:01:17,000
So, I lined up down in Oakland, and we didn't do course or transport it across the bay with a hundred other guys.

810
01:01:17,000 --> 01:01:22,000
You see, I'm told a strip there, and I said to the courseman, and the first courseman, I said,

811
01:01:22,000 --> 01:01:30,000
I said, I've had a recent appendectomy, and I said, I'm supposed to be deferred for six. He says, get in line.

812
01:01:30,000 --> 01:01:37,000
I got in line. I came to the next courseman, I said the same thing to him, he said, get in line.

813
01:01:37,000 --> 01:01:49,000
Went through all the tests and so on and passed them all, and came to the last guy who was an officer there, and there's a guy who was supposed to test for their mentally fifties as psychologists.

814
01:01:49,000 --> 01:02:04,000
And he looked me up and down and said, you had a recent appendectomy, and I said, yes, I've been trying to tell him that all day long. He grabs my papers and he writes deferred.

815
01:02:04,000 --> 01:02:21,000
And lastly, the war ended, there was still going to be occupation forces, and the war ended, of course, in the Pacific and August of 1945.

816
01:02:21,000 --> 01:02:29,000
And a lot of the military were being decommissioned and sent home and so on.

817
01:02:29,000 --> 01:02:36,000
And then the year were rolled around and the question was, who were they going to have in the occupation forces?

818
01:02:36,000 --> 01:02:44,000
And at this point, of course, there was no further need of my services than this war work, and so I was eligible for this.

819
01:02:44,000 --> 01:03:00,000
But on the second of February in 1946, I turned 26, and they didn't take anybody over 25.

820
01:03:00,000 --> 01:03:18,000
So then I was automatically out of the occupation draft group, and then I entered Caltech in the spring of that year, left Sheldon Elementary Company.

821
01:03:18,000 --> 01:03:36,000
Well, there were several things. The Japanese, of course, had succeeded in overrunning all of the plantation that provided latex for natural rubber, which is of course really needed during the war.

822
01:03:36,000 --> 01:03:51,000
And so synthetic rubber had been discovered, and there were all sorts of ways of making synthetic rubber. So I worked a lot on the problem of synthetic rubber.

823
01:03:51,000 --> 01:04:06,000
Another thing that developed about this time during the war was the discovery of the efficacy of penicillin, which is being produced in a traditional way.

824
01:04:06,000 --> 01:04:26,000
In our area, by cutter laboratories, it existed in either in Emoryville or in Berkeley or Oakland, right down there close to the bay. They had huge vats, and they cultivated this and separated the penicillin, which was distributed to the armed forces, was not available to civilians at all.

825
01:04:26,000 --> 01:04:34,000
At this time, and I worked on the extraction, the methods for extracting penicillin from this.

826
01:04:34,000 --> 01:04:46,000
The third thing that I did was that was probably the most interesting, in many ways, was an aviation gasoline inhibitor.

827
01:04:46,000 --> 01:05:06,000
Now, aviation gasoline, in that time, was hundred octane fuel, because all the aircraft were propeller driven, and there was a high performance engines that required that level of anonaut quality.

828
01:05:06,000 --> 01:05:17,000
This was particularly during the North African campaign, and these tanks of hundred octane fuel were shipped across, and then they had to stand in the desert.

829
01:05:17,000 --> 01:05:28,000
Now, one thing that happens to gasoline is that over time, they tend to form some gum, which settles out to the bottom.

830
01:05:28,000 --> 01:05:37,000
Now, that gum, if it gets into the engines, of course, can be a very serious matter.

831
01:05:37,000 --> 01:05:49,000
So, they apply what are called inhibitors to delay or greatly slow down the formation of this gum.

832
01:05:49,000 --> 01:06:03,000
And the stockpiles of fuel there in North Africa had in them a die, a red die.

833
01:06:03,000 --> 01:06:10,000
It turned out that when the gum was formed, this red die would be a clue to take down the fuel with changed color.

834
01:06:10,000 --> 01:06:24,000
So, the sergeants running the dump would realize what it was going on, and they would then use this deteriorated fuel and jeeps, and then motor vehicles of various kinds.

835
01:06:24,000 --> 01:06:33,000
Well, of course, it's obvious that what you want to do is to prevent this from happening as long as possible, because that's expensive fuel to be using in jeeps.

836
01:06:33,000 --> 01:06:42,000
Then it turns out that a lot of the time that the stuff was gone, the die was disappearing, the fuel was still good.

837
01:06:42,000 --> 01:07:11,000
Well, we had a special inhibitor that was better than anything in use that we were developing and testing in the desert with a drum, that we have mounted on the demahave desert at an army base with a bunch of thermocouples all through it, because we needed to figure out, we needed to figure out how quickly the gum formed,

838
01:07:11,000 --> 01:07:23,000
in accordance with weather conditions. I mean, if you store these drums I mentioned in North Africa and the winter there's no problem it's cold, and in the summer it goes to pot very quickly.

839
01:07:23,000 --> 01:07:34,000
Well, how do you know that because you don't know what the temperature inside the fuel is, because in the summer a barrel at the bottom might be relatively cool and one at the top would be totally gone.

840
01:07:34,000 --> 01:07:58,000
We had a way, we put these thermocouples all through this test drum, and then we could measure the rate of formation of gum as a function of, well, we took these temperature data from the thermocouples all through the drum and worked that up into something that we could call an effective temperature for the whole drum.

841
01:07:58,000 --> 01:08:04,000
And we could predict from a thermocouple in any place what the effective temperature was in the whole drum.

842
01:08:04,000 --> 01:08:18,000
And that would tell us how long that fuel could be expected to last, and so we did that in addition to developing and testing our inhibitor which turned out to be very good.

843
01:08:18,000 --> 01:08:33,000
Well, the war ended before the inhibitor could actually be used, and then of course the fuel now is not under octane anymore, so that never got into production, but if the war gone on much longer it would have been.

844
01:08:33,000 --> 01:08:48,000
That's the kind of thing that I did, and all of this laboratory work was of tremendous aid to me when I entered graduate school because I know how to use my hands, I've been doing it for three years in the laboratory.

845
01:08:48,000 --> 01:08:51,000
This job was in Southern California.

846
01:08:51,000 --> 01:08:53,000
Yeah, Caltech.

847
01:08:53,000 --> 01:08:54,000
Oh, is that Caltech?

848
01:08:54,000 --> 01:08:56,000
I went to Caltech.

849
01:08:56,000 --> 01:09:00,000
Oh, the shell was it, it was an Emoryville.

850
01:09:00,000 --> 01:09:02,000
It was called shell development.

851
01:09:02,000 --> 01:09:11,000
Emoryville is a small on-play between Berkeley and Oklahoma on the Bay.

852
01:09:11,000 --> 01:09:13,000
Well, we're at about an hour and 10 minutes.

853
01:09:13,000 --> 01:09:17,000
Do you want to keep going or do you want to?

854
01:09:17,000 --> 01:09:19,000
Well, I can go a longer.

855
01:09:19,000 --> 01:09:24,000
I probably should leave here about quarter to twelve, and if you want to.

856
01:09:24,000 --> 01:09:25,000
Okay.

857
01:09:25,000 --> 01:09:27,000
Or we can do whatever you like.

858
01:09:27,000 --> 01:09:33,000
Well, if you're, if you're, if you're, if you're left, if I'd like to keep going.

859
01:09:33,000 --> 01:09:37,000
So, you finished up at shell, and then you went to Caltech.

860
01:09:37,000 --> 01:09:40,000
How did, what was the process by which that happened?

861
01:09:40,000 --> 01:09:42,000
How did you mind at the Caltech?

862
01:09:42,000 --> 01:09:46,000
Well, the laboratory work,

863
01:09:46,000 --> 01:09:48,000
and it's shell.

864
01:09:48,000 --> 01:09:52,000
I should say just a little bit more about that.

865
01:09:52,000 --> 01:09:55,000
Was a small laboratory.

866
01:09:55,000 --> 01:09:58,000
You know, a shell development.

867
01:09:58,000 --> 01:10:01,000
There were all sorts of projects distributed all over.

868
01:10:01,000 --> 01:10:06,000
There was a motor lab out and back, in which gasoline's were tested.

869
01:10:06,000 --> 01:10:09,000
I was in the research end, and there were,

870
01:10:09,000 --> 01:10:13,000
where the head of my small laboratory,

871
01:10:13,000 --> 01:10:18,000
and another guy who had been working there for a long time,

872
01:10:18,000 --> 01:10:24,000
and I was brought in as a third guy to help these people.

873
01:10:24,000 --> 01:10:28,000
We became all three of us, very close friends,

874
01:10:28,000 --> 01:10:33,000
and as social as well as in a professional sense.

875
01:10:34,000 --> 01:10:40,000
The man who, who headed as a name,

876
01:10:40,000 --> 01:10:44,000
Daniel B. Luther Jr.

877
01:10:44,000 --> 01:10:49,000
And he was a remarkable person.

878
01:10:49,000 --> 01:10:53,000
He was a very good scientist.

879
01:10:53,000 --> 01:10:58,000
And at the same time, when the war was over, during the war,

880
01:10:58,000 --> 01:11:02,000
he got very interested, partly because of this North African stuff.

881
01:11:02,000 --> 01:11:10,000
In climate, and thereby associated himself with geography.

882
01:11:10,000 --> 01:11:15,000
So he knew a great deal about geography all over the world,

883
01:11:15,000 --> 01:11:19,000
and especially about climate changes in temperature and so on.

884
01:11:19,000 --> 01:11:26,000
And he used to amuse us by coming up with some facts that you know that you didn't know.

885
01:11:26,000 --> 01:11:38,000
He said, where do you think the rainyest July in the world is?

886
01:11:38,000 --> 01:11:42,000
Where is the place where the rainyest July takes place?

887
01:11:42,000 --> 01:11:45,000
Well, right away, you think monsoon or something.

888
01:11:45,000 --> 01:11:51,000
It turns out there is some village called Charapunji India,

889
01:11:51,000 --> 01:11:56,000
and India, and he said in the monsoon season,

890
01:11:56,000 --> 01:12:04,000
he announced to us that it had something like 240 inches of rain in the month of July.

891
01:12:04,000 --> 01:12:07,000
These are the kind of facts that he would come up with.

892
01:12:07,000 --> 01:12:11,000
Well, the reason I mentioned all this is that after the war was over,

893
01:12:11,000 --> 01:12:15,000
he retired from shell as a chemist,

894
01:12:15,000 --> 01:12:19,000
but became so knowledgeable in this other area

895
01:12:19,000 --> 01:12:26,000
and he was appointed an adjunct professor of geography at Cal.

896
01:12:26,000 --> 01:12:31,000
And as time went on, he built quite a reputation in that field.

897
01:12:31,000 --> 01:12:37,000
He came to Oregon State, gave lectures here, was invited up on the geography department.

898
01:12:37,000 --> 01:12:42,000
He was a very, very interesting guy.

899
01:12:42,000 --> 01:12:45,000
The other fellow is Joseph's interesting.

900
01:12:45,000 --> 01:12:50,000
His name was Aldo, the Benedictus, and he was an Italian, obviously.

901
01:12:50,000 --> 01:12:52,000
He came from an Italian family.

902
01:12:52,000 --> 01:12:56,000
He was engaged to the head of business and making pasta.

903
01:12:56,000 --> 01:13:00,000
And one time he told me, he says, don't let him kid you.

904
01:13:00,000 --> 01:13:02,000
He says the dough is all the same.

905
01:13:02,000 --> 01:13:06,000
It's just the die that makes the difference between pasta.

906
01:13:06,000 --> 01:13:10,000
So the texture is different depending on the die, but not the dough.

907
01:13:10,000 --> 01:13:13,000
Well, Benny graduated from Cal.

908
01:13:13,000 --> 01:13:19,000
He was an excellent student, but he had a family of several children,

909
01:13:19,000 --> 01:13:21,000
and he had to go to work.

910
01:13:21,000 --> 01:13:26,000
But not having a doctor's degree, he was not running the lab, you see.

911
01:13:26,000 --> 01:13:32,000
But Dan Luton treated him in every way as an equal.

912
01:13:32,000 --> 01:13:35,000
He had his own projects and everything.

913
01:13:35,000 --> 01:13:38,000
Well, he spoke Italian fluently.

914
01:13:39,000 --> 01:13:45,000
And Shell had a occasion to want somebody that knew Italian very well

915
01:13:45,000 --> 01:13:50,000
to serve as a translator and so on.

916
01:13:50,000 --> 01:13:56,000
And after the war, he moved out of chemistry into marketing for Shell,

917
01:13:56,000 --> 01:14:02,000
where his language skills could be useful and he moved to New York.

918
01:14:02,000 --> 01:14:05,000
Well, he did very well in the company.

919
01:14:05,000 --> 01:14:11,000
He moved up the ranks, finally when he retired officially from that aspect of Shell,

920
01:14:11,000 --> 01:14:15,000
they moved back to Berkeley, he and his wife and family.

921
01:14:15,000 --> 01:14:19,000
Guess his kids were grown and they lived there at the time.

922
01:14:19,000 --> 01:14:29,000
And then he told me he became very wealthy after he retired.

923
01:14:29,000 --> 01:14:35,000
And he told me how this happened.

924
01:14:35,000 --> 01:14:47,000
There is a company knowing as...

925
01:14:47,000 --> 01:14:50,000
I'm thinking advanced micro-devices.

926
01:14:50,000 --> 01:14:51,000
It's not that one.

927
01:14:51,000 --> 01:14:53,000
It's another one that makes chips.

928
01:14:53,000 --> 01:14:55,000
It's the biggest chip maker in the world now.

929
01:14:55,000 --> 01:14:58,000
Chips for computers and so on.

930
01:14:58,000 --> 01:15:00,000
Pardon?

931
01:15:00,000 --> 01:15:02,000
No, no.

932
01:15:02,000 --> 01:15:04,000
No, they make...

933
01:15:04,000 --> 01:15:08,000
Well, I'm sorry, I'm a spoke.

934
01:15:08,000 --> 01:15:14,000
I think they make the devices for making chips.

935
01:15:14,000 --> 01:15:19,000
But he told me, many told me, we told him, many.

936
01:15:19,000 --> 01:15:24,000
That he was approached by some people about this project.

937
01:15:24,000 --> 01:15:27,000
And he said about five or six of them sat down

938
01:15:27,000 --> 01:15:35,000
around the kitchen table in his house in Berkeley.

939
01:15:35,000 --> 01:15:41,000
And he decided he... they all put up $10,000.

940
01:15:41,000 --> 01:15:45,000
And that company just grew like wildfire

941
01:15:45,000 --> 01:15:51,000
and he ended a multi-millionaire just by just thinking that money.

942
01:15:51,000 --> 01:15:56,000
And so he endowed a chair at Berkeley in chemistry,

943
01:15:56,000 --> 01:15:59,000
called the All of the Benedictus Chair of Chemistry.

944
01:15:59,000 --> 01:16:03,000
His wife went to UCLA and was an nutritionist.

945
01:16:03,000 --> 01:16:08,000
And he set up a similar thing in her name at UCLA

946
01:16:08,000 --> 01:16:10,000
with another million dollars.

947
01:16:10,000 --> 01:16:11,000
So this was done years ago.

948
01:16:11,000 --> 01:16:14,000
It must be worth a lot more than that now.

949
01:16:14,000 --> 01:16:19,000
So I thought that was quite a remarkable story for a guy

950
01:16:19,000 --> 01:16:24,000
who spent his youth making pasta and working

951
01:16:24,000 --> 01:16:28,000
in a chemistry laboratory to end up like that.

952
01:16:28,000 --> 01:16:33,000
Okay, so Caltech, what decided me to go there?

953
01:16:33,000 --> 01:16:36,000
Well, I was thinking about going there

954
01:16:36,000 --> 01:16:38,000
and I wrote that you see Gilbert and he said, well,

955
01:16:38,000 --> 01:16:39,000
you have to.

956
01:16:39,000 --> 01:16:41,000
You said, you know, there's a very good university right there

957
01:16:41,000 --> 01:16:42,000
where you're working.

958
01:16:42,000 --> 01:16:44,000
That's the University of California.

959
01:16:44,000 --> 01:16:47,000
For some reason, I wasn't interested in going to Cal.

960
01:16:47,000 --> 01:16:50,000
I don't know why.

961
01:16:50,000 --> 01:16:53,000
But it's a tremendous institution.

